<TITLE>Trump and Putin connect over Middle East and repairing relationship</TITLE>
<TEXT>
President Donald Trump had a “positive call” with Russian President Vladimir Putin on Saturday, during which the two promised to cooperate on destroying ISIS in Syrian and repair U.S. and Russian relations. 
 
The discussion was part of a diplomatic effort to connect over the phone with foreign leaders from countries including Japan, Germany, France and Australia. 
 
“The positive call was a significant start to improving the relationship between the United States and Russia that is in need of repair,” the White House said in a readout of the conversation. “Both President Trump and President Putin are hopeful that after today’s call the two sides can move quickly to tackle terrorism and other important issues of mutual concern.” 
 
A statement from the Kremlin’s office went even further to solidify the ties between the two, saying that the leaders “agreed to maintain regular personal contacts.” 
 
The Kremlin’s statement said that the two spoke about the “Ukraine Crisis” and repairing economic relationships, suggesting that Trump said he would be open to lifting sanctions against Russia. 
 
“The sides stressed the importance of rebuilding mutually beneficial trade and economic ties between the two countriesâ business communities, which could give an additional impetus to progressive and sustainable development of bilateral relations,” the Kremlin’s office said in a statement. 
 
“During the conversation, both sides expressed their readiness to make active joint efforts to stabilize and develop Russia-US cooperation on a constructive, equitable and mutually beneficial basis.” 
 
On Friday, Trump said he hoped to have a “fantastic relationship” with Putin. Following Trump’s pledge to restore relations with Russia, there has been some speculation that he will lift economic sanctions on the country that were instated for it’s invasion in Ukraine. 
 
Trump’s close relationship with Putin has been an issue of concern for the defense agencies who found evidence of Russian hacking to meddle in the U.S. elections. 
 
Trump started his day with a morning call with Japanese Premiere Shinzo Abe. The two leaders affirmed “the ironclad U.S. commitment to ensuring the security of Japan” including an agreement to cooperate on the threat posed by North Korea, according to a White House readout of the meeting. 
 
There was also an agreement to “deepen” bilateral trade following Trump’s executive order this week to pull out of the Transpacific Trade Partnership. 
 
Abe agreed to come to Washington on February 10. Secretary of Defense General Mattis will visit the region, including Japan. 

