Following the call, Trump had a 45 minute conversation with German Chancellor Angela Merkel that covered topics from reinforcing a U.S. commitment NATO, combatting terrrorism and dealing with Russian aggression, according to a White House re-out. 
 
While Trump has been critical of NATO, calling it “obsolete” on the campaign trail, his statements seem open to supporting NATO as long as EU partners agree to pay two percent of their budgets to the defense alliance. At a press conference in Washington yesterday, British Prime Minister Theresa revealed a piece of their conversation on the diplomatically sensitive topic for Russia’s neighbors in Europe saying that Trump pledged his “100 percent commitment” to NATO. 
 
“The President and Chancellor also agreed on the NATO Alliance’s fundamental importance to the broader transatlantic relationship and its role in ensuring the peace and stability of our North Atlantic community,” the White House said in a statement. 
 
“In this vein, the leaders recognized that NATO must be capable of confronting 21st century threats and that our common defense requires appropriate investment in military capabilities to ensure all Allies are contributing their fair share to our collective security.” 
 
Francois Hollande reaffirmed France’s commitment to the United Nations and NATO, and warned Trump against being too protectionist. 
 
“In an unstable and uncertain world, turning inward would be a dead-end,” he said, according to a statement from the French government. 
 
The White House has not issued a readout on the call. 
 
Trump accepted Merkel’s invitation to the G-20 in Hamburg in July and also promised to visit Washington “soon,” according to the readout. 
 
Chief of Staff Reince Priebus, Press Secretary Sean Spicer, National Security advisor General Michael Flynn and senior advisor Steve Bannon were all present in the room during Trump’s call with Putin. 
 
Translators were used during the conversation with Putin, Abe, Merkel and Hollande. 
 
After signing three executive orders in the late afternoon, Trump started his call with Australian Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull.
